Adapt_main_4_mc_24_TEXT: raising wages (increases insurance and other factors), changes in liquor code, changes in Legal/HR operations such as C.R.S § 8-74-10
Adapt_Main_5_open: We need a moratorium on legislation and regulations for two years. Allow businesses to get caught up with all the current rules. It's been a whirlwind of changes since COVID. I think a lot of "good intent" is happening, but it's too much for small businesses to keep up and stay 100% compliant. Things like the $0.27 delivery fee made it where we just completely cut out the delivery. It was already a struggle for us with the liquor board adding a requirement to document (and store) delivery information. The extra fee to the state (and tracking of the fee) seems simple, but I don't have staff trained to help with all the changes. So it falls on me. I attend so many seminars and webinars to try and stay up-t0-date, but every change comes with 4-8 hours of work on my side to implement new processes. Then I have to train my managers and staff on absolutely everything.

Adapt_main_4_mc_27_TEXT: My company serves a very specific music industry niche, which unfortunately has not been able to recover since the pandemic. I'm still looking for work to supplement my income. These options don't apply to my small business.
Adapt_Main_5_open:
Quick answer, at this point, nothing. It's already been destroyed.

For 25 years, my small business has been dependent on bands touring and playing live. When everything shut down, initially we all figured it would be for a few weeks or maybe a month. But because of the inaction taken at the federal level (aka the dumpster fire that was #45), the music industry (live touring) stayed shut down for about 18 months straight. Most of my clients were forced to pivot, so I lost 5 of my 6+ annual clients. They all said they planned to come back once bands were touring, but none have. So, I trusted what I was told, waited for them to return, worked odd jobs/projects for supplemental income, but used up all of my savings trying to survive in the meantime. But have actively been trying to find permanent work for the past 6 months. I have a very eclectic set of skills, I know I will be a great asset to anyone who gives me a chance, but no one has taken that leap so far. So, I will just continue to keep trying.

Covid destroyed my business of 25 years. I trusted and put faith in long term clients, when I obviously shouldn't have. The past few years have sucked.

Adapt_main_4_mc_24_TEXT: Referring to shut downs and restrictions for restaurants
Adapt_Main_5_open: Consistency in product costs would help as so many are forever changing/increasing and the small business, such as mine, cannot afford to make these changes to our menus every time. It's very labor intensive to keep up with these changes taking away from the business.  Also, alot of the programs I was introduced to required a business provide tax information for 2019 or 2020 and my business started in 2020. I took over my unit in December 2019 and the world shut down in March 2020. I wasn't able to get licensed, inspections and other requirements due to shut downs. I was able to open my doors (after selling my home to continue the rent payments/no revenue) in July of 2020 and had no funding assistance at the time due to lack of required documents. I was fortunate enough to receive the Loan and stay afloat. I am not aware of many other programs that a business that just opened when the Covid pandemic became a thing, can utilize without such requirements.

Adapt_main_4_mc_24_TEXT: Regulation related to Medicaid services delivery
Adapt_Main_5_open: We are really struggling to retain and recruit skilled employees. Because we serve Medicaid, there is a ceiling on how much we can pay employees. We have maximized employee compensation and invested heavily in other benefits that are in demand. We really need 8 more clinicians to remain profitable and we struggle to find them; we are only able to hire about 1 every other month, and sometimes we lose employees or full-time employees downgrade to part-time employees. We are advocating hard to raise reimbursement rates so that we can pay our professionals a competitive salary. ("Private Pay" competitors that don't work with Medicaid or insurance can pay more than we can). I lose so much sleep and have built up so much anxiety over the past 2.5 years because of recruiting and retention. Right now we are not profitable, and I am responsible for this business and our payroll, so I am petrified at the personal impact this could have if I need to personally fund our business (and there are limits to that).

Bhea_Opres_6_open: Customer Satisfaction, is huge because it keeps customers coming back which keeps us a flout. Adapt_Main_5_open:
We are a newer company starting in 2019 right before the pandemic, and during that time there was a lack of new jobs starting because everyone was uncertain to what was going to happen. During the pandemic we have had shortages on every material this is resulting in high prices and low inventory, which affects small newer businesses like us because we are one just starting and our capital is low. Credit is scared because larger outfits are able to purchase material at higher costs and with cash so it hurts us. All while still having the same operational costs. The housing market is at a all time hard making it hard for employees, they need their pay to be alot higher then minimum wage in order for them to be able to keep a roof over their family's head so that increase in cost is also high. 

I think time in a normal economy will help us to be more stable, as it would any new business. I also thing having the right funding or the same access to capital to meet opportunities. Being able to estimate and land the right contracts.

Adapt_Main_5_open: Travel and related work is subject to the whims of government and their reactions to Covid and other threats. Since 2020 my thriving, growing practice got devastated by lack of income, lack of clients and then, as things opened back up, an influx of people willing to work for free. I can't pay my mortgage and corporate bills on "free." My corporate clients dried up and many of my international clients either went out of business or had to retrench and can't pay. I have tried writing for multiple platforms only to have them change their payment agorithms, and overnight have my income cut by 90%. I am exhausted, overwhelmed and bloody well defeated. The grants kept me alive and out of bankruptcy. I haven't given up but Jesus Christ.

Adapt_Main_5_open: We were heavily relying on Federal Aid. The Restaurant Revitalization Act ran out of money and only funded 1/3 of our colleagues. Inflation hit really high we had to use all of our savings and maxed all of my cards to keep my restaurant afloat. The last Hail Mary was applying for the SBA EIDL Loan….I even had my local congressman involved with their contact at the sba….then the SBA ran out of money., however I’m the following week, the SBA said there was $123 Billion Funds left from COVID money. $47 Billion of that could have saved the undfunded restaurant. We could not compete with wages and inflation that received the Restaurant Revitalization Fund, instead we were forced to close permanently but stuck with a mountain of debt

Adapt_main_4_mc_24: Legislation/regulation that generated excessive burden (please explain)
Adapt_Main_5_open: HIRING:  We have been challenged to hire qualified employees for years--we receive few applicants and mostly unqualified applicants, but rarely someone with the potential we are looking for.  Without reliable employees, I am forced to shadow existing employees, a huge reduction in my productivity as a small business owner--and consequently a reduction in my ability to engage in forward looking activities for the business.  COST OF EMPLOYEES AND TRAINING:  Higher costs for unskilled labor is killing small businesses.  I know of no job training or incentive programs that are offered byDenver or Colorado to address this.  REAL ESTATE:  There has been no growth in the commercial real estate market in years, plus the higher cost of NNNs inDenver (and beyond), which limits our growth into new locations.  BUSINESS GROWTH: I believe there is plenty of opportunity to grow the business, but postponing action on that only invites newer entrants into the markets I serve, further reducing my growth potential.  FUNDING:  I could bring on at least 3 new suppliers and a private label program if I could fund starter inventories for this purpose.  OUTREACH:  I work 6 days/week--and have for the last 4 years--to keep my business going.  My time is largely preoccupied with the day-in-day-out activities of the business, not forward looking outreach, new locations and new brands.  SALES TAX: I also find the sales tax environment in Colorado to be unnecessarily time-consuming and complicated, a detriment to every small business in the State.  It's poorly conceived and administered--and the legislature and governor are doing nothing to rectify this situation.

Adapt_Main_5_open:
It would be great if smaller businesses/ solopreneurs like mine had access to funding. It was frustrating to be asking for small amounts of 5k to 10k to keep my business afloat during Covid hardships and being told I didn’t qualify. 

My business provided support to help businesses pivot and overcome stress and obstacles during the economic strains. While helping others and volunteering with energize colorado to help people gain access to funding and survive hardships during Covid, I was denied funding due to my business not having employees, not being at a certain level of revenue and other assumptions around not getting ‘extra’ credit for my minority status. I support fully making funding accessible to all persons, especially those who have historically had issues gaining access to funding but if you deny others in need because they are not part of that group then it swings a pendulum in the other direction.

Adapt_Main_5_open: My business is located in an area the went through a "boom" a few years prior to the pandemic lockdown.  This mad rent more expensive and, ultimately, untenable.  I was faced with the decision to either close or downsize significantly.  I chose the latter path and move locations.  Additionally, I personally was in a major car accident in October 2021 and am still in recovery.  My goals at the moment are to keep it operational in order to pay for the EIDL loan taken out to cover 2020 expenses and I continue to eliminate unnecessary operating expenses.  I  used  part of the Energize Colorado Grant the funds for needed display fixture upgrades.  Although I am uncertain about the immediate future due to how much my injuries have set me back, I hope to eventually be able to focus on growing the business in 2023 as I doubt I could sell it given it's current state.

Adapt_Main_5_open: I need cash on hand. Period. The government pretends the impact of COVID is over. The reality is that me, and every small business owner, is hanging on for dear life and every available source of government/public assistance is either tapped out or about to be shuttered. I feel angry knowing that large corporations aren't paying taxes while making money off the backs of consumers who are squeezed to the max. These corporations should be contributing to an equity fund for small business owners. Much of the problems we have are their fault lately. Meanwhile, people like me are choosing whether to buy food or keep business open. EVERYONE needs to do more. The business climate isn't bad. It's hostile and it's ruining the lives of small business owners everywhere.

Adapt_Main_5_open: What would’ve really helped would’ve been if we could’ve been awarded a grant that was created by high our state to help with overhead costs because loans or something I have to pay back, which is difficult after a pandemic for a dance school. When speaking to the people they gave the grant, they admitted they didn’t have a strict enough process, and we’re giving grants away to people who did not have overhead such as leasing a building or a space of their own. I still feel very hurt and poorly treated in regards to the Colorado arts relief grant that was created for people like me. REP, Amebilia referred us and recommended us for this grant because of this our program still suffers, and is working hard to regain our footing. So what would help is this… it would help to have people running the grant process that understand how it should be run and have certain limit set so that businesses that educate you through adult and give back to communities can receive these grant monies, even though we’re a small business and not a nonprofit. Unfortunately we’re seeing a lot of companies that don’t have overhead receive this grant and they also are putting on performances that are creating revenue for themselves where many of us just needed the revenue to survive to pay rent, electricity, etc..
